import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base title="Context Injection: +34pp Across 26 AI Models — ostk" description="How invisible context injection improved AI coding agent performance by +34 percentage points across 26 models. Budget models match frontier performance. Data from 1,664 runs.">
  <div class="container">
    <h1>Context Injection: +34pp Mean Improvement Across 26 Models</h1>

    <p class="lede">
      Silently injecting project context into an AI agent&rsquo;s system prompt improved debugging performance by a mean of <strong>+34.3 percentage points</strong> across 26 models and 1,664 runs. Budget models matched frontier performance. The effect was consistent across all 8 vendors tested.
    </p>

    <section>
      <h2>The experiment</h2>
      <p><a href="https://needle-bench.cc">needle-bench</a> tests AI coding agents on 32 real bugs frozen in Docker containers. Each model gets shell access and one instruction: <em>find the needle</em>. The test suite passes or it doesn&rsquo;t.</p>
      <p>Every model runs twice:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Bare</strong> &mdash; generic system prompt + bash. No project context.</li>
        <li><strong>OS (silent)</strong> &mdash; identical prompt, but project context (README, file tree, test output, recent errors) is injected into the system prompt. The model cannot detect which arm it&rsquo;s in.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The context injection is invisible. Same tools, same turn limits, same token budgets. The only difference is what the model knows before it starts exploring.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The results</h2>
      <div class="data-table-wrap">
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th></th><th>Mean</th><th>Median</th><th>Models improved</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Bare</td><td class="num">34.9%</td><td class="num">15.6%</td><td class="num">&mdash;</td></tr>
            <tr><td>With context</td><td class="num">69.2%</td><td class="num">72.9%</td><td class="num">&mdash;</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Delta</strong></td><td class="num accent"><strong>+34.3pp</strong></td><td class="num accent"><strong>+37.5pp</strong></td><td class="num"><strong>23/26</strong></td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Why does this work?</h2>
      <p>AI coding agents waste most of their turns on orientation. In the bare arm, a typical agent spends 5&ndash;10 turns reading README files, listing directories, running tests, and mapping the codebase before it even starts debugging. That&rsquo;s 5&ndash;10 turns of token budget spent on information that could have been provided upfront.</p>
      <p>Context injection front-loads this information. The agent&rsquo;s first turn already knows:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>What the project does (README summary)</li>
        <li>Where the relevant files are (file tree, filtered to likely areas)</li>
        <li>What&rsquo;s failing (test output, error messages)</li>
        <li>What was recently changed (git log, diff summary)</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The agent skips exploration and starts debugging immediately. Fewer turns wasted, more turns available for the actual fix.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Budget models close the gap</h2>
      <p>Context injection lets cheap models match expensive ones.</p>
      <div class="data-table-wrap">
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Comparison</th><th>Rate</th><th>Resolve</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Claude Opus 4 bare</td><td class="num muted">$15/MTok</td><td class="num">90.6%</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Claude Haiku 4.5 + context</td><td class="num muted">$0.80/MTok</td><td class="num accent">90.6%</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>Haiku with context matches Opus without it &mdash; at roughly <strong>1/19th the cost</strong>. The same pattern repeats across vendors:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>GPT-4o + context</strong> (81.2%) beats <strong>GPT-4.1 bare</strong> (50.0%)</li>
        <li><strong>Gemini Flash + context</strong> (65.6%) beats <strong>Gemini 2.5 Pro bare</strong> (28.1%)</li>
        <li><strong>Devstral 24B + context</strong> (75.0%) beats <strong>GPT-4.1 bare</strong> (50.0%) &mdash; an open 24B model outperforms a closed frontier model</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>How ostk does it</h2>
      <p>You get context injection as part of the boot sequence. When an agent starts, ostk reads your project state and assembles a context payload:</p>
      <div class="code-block">
        <pre><code>$ ostk init        # one-time project setup
$ ostk boot        # run with context injection

# What the agent sees (invisible, in system prompt):
# - Project: api-server (Node.js + Express)
# - Files: 47 files, 3,200 LOC
# - Tests: 2 failing (auth.test.js:42, auth.test.js:67)
# - Recent: modified auth/middleware.js 2 hours ago
# - Error: "TypeError: Cannot read property 'role' of undefined"</code></pre>
      </div>
      <p>The agent receives this as part of its system prompt. It doesn&rsquo;t know it&rsquo;s been given context &mdash; it just starts with better information. No special model configuration, no fine-tuning, no prompt engineering.</p>
      <p>This is what the needle-bench &ldquo;OS&rdquo; arm tests: can invisible context injection improve performance? Across 26 models and 1,664 runs, the answer is yes, by an average of 34.3 percentage points.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Beyond debugging</h2>
      <p>needle-bench measures debugging specifically, but the principle generalizes. Any task where an AI agent spends turns on orientation benefits from context injection:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Code review</strong> &mdash; agent knows the PR context, related files, and test coverage before reading the diff</li>
        <li><strong>Feature implementation</strong> &mdash; agent knows the architecture, existing patterns, and dependency constraints upfront</li>
        <li><strong>Refactoring</strong> &mdash; agent knows what depends on what before it starts moving code</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The mechanism is the same: reduce exploration turns, increase productive turns.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="takeaway">
      <h2>Try it</h2>
      <p>ostk is free, open source, and local-first. Install it, run <code>ostk init</code> in your project, and see the difference.</p>
      <p><a href="/docs/">Read the docs</a> &middot; <a href="https://needle-bench.cc/insights/model-comparison/">See all 26 models</a> &middot; <a href="https://needle-bench.cc">Live leaderboard</a></p>
    </section>
  </div>
</Base>

